1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,960
 So network sockets are like phone calls for computers.

2
00:00:03,960 --> 00:00:05,880
 And literally, in the 1960s, when

3
00:00:05,880 --> 00:00:08,560
 they were designing the concept for network software,

4
00:00:08,560 --> 00:00:12,000
 that is the concept that they came up with.

5
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:16,320
 And that is that, in a sense, we make a call, we talk on the call,

6
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:17,360
 and we hang the phone up.

7
00:00:17,360 --> 00:00:19,700
 And as computers were going to share data,

8
00:00:19,700 --> 00:00:22,320
 and some computers were going to have data, and other computers

9
00:00:22,320 --> 00:00:25,680
 were going to want data, they thought, oh, the way to do this

10
00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:27,600
 is not necessarily have a permanent connection

11
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:30,040
 to that data, because there's going to be so many computers,

12
00:00:30,040 --> 00:00:33,480
 and so many sources of data, and so many computers that

13
00:00:33,480 --> 00:00:34,600
 want to consume those data.

14
00:00:34,600 --> 00:00:36,720
 And of course, in 1960, they had no imagination

15
00:00:36,720 --> 00:00:37,920
 that there would be billions.

16
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:40,760
 They just thought there would be 10,000.

17
00:00:40,760 --> 00:00:42,320
 And they thought that was a lot.

18
00:00:42,320 --> 00:00:44,760
 But they came up with a protocol that basically said,

19
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:49,000
 when you don't have continuous permanent access to data,

20
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,680
 you actually make a phone call.

21
00:00:50,680 --> 00:00:52,080
 You know where the data is at.

22
00:00:52,080 --> 00:00:55,680
 You kind of say, you dial up, you grab this stuff,

23
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:58,040
 you get it back, and then you let the connection go.

24
00:00:58,040 --> 00:01:01,280
 And so it means that with billions of computers,

25
00:01:01,280 --> 00:01:04,840
 each talking to each other, the network isn't so complex.

26
00:01:04,840 --> 00:01:09,680
 And so there's this connect, talk, disconnect.

27
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:11,120
 Connect, talk, disconnect.

28
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:15,840
 And it's the way the phone system in our world

29
00:01:15,840 --> 00:01:17,280
 scales to all the people, and it's

30
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:19,360
 the way the internet scales to all the people that

31
00:01:19,360 --> 00:01:21,360
 want to use that internet.

32
00:01:21,360 --> 00:01:25,760
 So this is made inside of software

33
00:01:25,760 --> 00:01:30,120
 using an abstraction, our library, called Sockets.

34
00:01:30,120 --> 00:01:34,240
 And Sockets really are computer phone calls.

35
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:36,720
 You know where you're going to call.

36
00:01:36,720 --> 00:01:39,720
 You can start the call, wait for them to answer.

37
00:01:39,720 --> 00:01:42,920
 Once they answer, there is a two-way communication.

38
00:01:42,920 --> 00:01:45,600
 It's kind of like a file, except that you

39
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:48,320
 can simultaneously read from the file and write from the file,

40
00:01:48,320 --> 00:01:50,880
 although it's important for the two cooperating

41
00:01:50,880 --> 00:01:53,760
 pieces of software to know who's going to read first

42
00:01:53,760 --> 00:01:55,960
 and who's going to write first, because it's

43
00:01:55,960 --> 00:01:58,360
 like if when you pick the phone up after it rings,

44
00:01:58,360 --> 00:02:00,840
 we all know to say, hello.

45
00:02:00,840 --> 00:02:02,520
 And that's kind of a protocol.

46
00:02:02,520 --> 00:02:05,080
 Who talks first is a protocol.

47
00:02:05,080 --> 00:02:06,840
 And then the person goes, who is this?

48
00:02:06,840 --> 00:02:09,280
 And then eventually conversations

49
00:02:09,280 --> 00:02:11,560
 happen pretty naturally.

50
00:02:11,560 --> 00:02:12,760
 Somebody talks, listens.

51
00:02:12,760 --> 00:02:14,400
 Someone else talks, listens.

52
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:18,120
 And that works, but there's complicated protocols.

53
00:02:18,120 --> 00:02:20,280
 And you can think of this not necessarily

54
00:02:20,280 --> 00:02:24,600
 as the browser on your laptop or phone

55
00:02:24,600 --> 00:02:27,080
 as talking to data on the server.

56
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:29,760
 It actually is talking to another program.

57
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:32,000
 And so even when it's just retrieving a file,

58
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,880
 it's talking to an application on that server.

59
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:38,160
 And that application is reading the file and sending it out.

60
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:39,680
 And we'll see that eventually how

61
00:02:39,680 --> 00:02:41,760
 we have to do that when we're doing things

62
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:43,280
 like uploading pictures.

63
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:45,840
 We upload pictures, and then we have to actually serve them

64
00:02:45,840 --> 00:02:46,440
 back out.

65
00:02:46,440 --> 00:02:48,360
 We can't just say, oh, the pictures are there.

66
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:49,400
 You can grab them.

67
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:52,520
 Because sometimes not everyone can see every picture.

68
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:54,640
 And so part of the software application

69
00:02:54,640 --> 00:02:58,200
 decides, if you are allowed to see this picture, I will send it.

70
00:02:58,200 --> 00:03:01,120
 If you're not allowed to see the picture, I will not send it.

71
00:03:01,120 --> 00:03:03,400
 And so that's where it's a piece of software

72
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:06,560
 that you're talking, even if you're looking at a picture.

73
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:08,360
 Sometimes that software is really simple

74
00:03:08,360 --> 00:03:11,280
 and you barely notice it.

75
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:13,000
 But there is software in the loop.

76
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:15,200
 It's not like you just go straight to data.

77
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:18,560
 It is really two pieces of computer software

78
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:20,000
 talking to each other.

79
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,400
 And we use the internet as that intermediary

80
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:26,240
 to allow that conversation to happen.

81
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:29,160
 So if you read my book about the TCP/IP,

82
00:03:29,160 --> 00:03:31,200
 you'll learn this in super great detail.

83
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:36,240
 But every computer has an IP address.

84
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:37,320
 It is a number.

85
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:38,660
 There are two kinds of addresses.

86
00:03:38,660 --> 00:03:41,840
 There's IPv4 and IPv6.

87
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:45,760
 IPv4 version 4 is the one that's got four dotted numbers,

88
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:51,280
 like 142.16.42.14.

89
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:52,920
 But within each of those, they have what's

90
00:03:52,920 --> 00:03:55,000
 called a TCP port number.

91
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,240
 And because this whole internet thing

92
00:03:57,240 --> 00:03:59,280
 is applications talking to applications,

93
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:02,880
 we need to have a good way to know which application we're

94
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:03,400
 talking to.

95
00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:06,120
 And that's where TCP port numbers come in.

96
00:04:06,120 --> 00:04:10,360
 And you can think of this as like a phone extension.

97
00:04:10,360 --> 00:04:15,680
 So you have a phone number, and then you have extension 1436.

98
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:17,640
 And so TCP port numbers are like that.

99
00:04:17,640 --> 00:04:22,480
 So we can not have a specific address for every application,

100
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:25,560
 but an application that has an address and a port

101
00:04:25,560 --> 00:04:28,520
 within that address, or a phone number and an extension

102
00:04:28,520 --> 00:04:30,840
 within that phone number.

103
00:04:30,840 --> 00:04:32,840
 And so you can look these things up.

104
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:37,320
 Port 25 is used for email, server-to-server communication.

105
00:04:37,320 --> 00:04:39,600
 In the old days, we used this thing called Telnet.

106
00:04:39,600 --> 00:04:42,440
 We'll talk about that on port 23.

107
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:46,440
 And so the client is on the right-hand side.

108
00:04:46,440 --> 00:04:49,360
 And it might be a computer where you've got a keyboard,

109
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:50,320
 and it's you.

110
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:52,560
 Or it might be a server that's got some mail that's

111
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:54,200
 being forwarded from somewhere.

112
00:04:54,200 --> 00:04:57,180
 And they all talk, and they connect to an IP address.

113
00:04:57,180 --> 00:05:02,440
 In this case, 7420828177 is the IP address of this computer.

114
00:05:02,440 --> 00:05:04,960
 And then port 25 is the extension

115
00:05:04,960 --> 00:05:08,440
 where one computer sends email to another computer.

116
00:05:08,440 --> 00:05:10,880
 And each of the arrows in between them

117
00:05:10,880 --> 00:05:12,320
 is a separate protocol.

118
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:14,160
 So if you're talking to an email server,

119
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:15,820
 you expect to talk an email protocol.

120
00:05:15,820 --> 00:05:17,480
 And if you're talking to a login server,

121
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:18,560
 you have a login protocol.

122
00:05:18,560 --> 00:05:19,820
 That's kind of the simplest one.

123
00:05:19,820 --> 00:05:21,120
 Or a web server.

124
00:05:21,120 --> 00:05:24,560
 Web server can be on port 80 if it's unsecure.

125
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:28,600
 Preferred, of course, is HTTPS, which is on port 443.

126
00:05:28,600 --> 00:05:32,840
 If you have a mail application, like say Thunderbird,

127
00:05:32,840 --> 00:05:36,580
 that's reading Gmail, it talks to ports 109 or 110

128
00:05:36,580 --> 00:05:39,800
 or a couple of other ones that are ways for a mailbox

129
00:05:39,800 --> 00:05:43,800
 application to talk a protocol to a server-based mailbox

130
00:05:43,800 --> 00:05:46,600
 to retrieve the new messages or delete a message or view

131
00:05:46,600 --> 00:05:48,240
 a message or whatever.

132
00:05:48,240 --> 00:05:52,640
 So there are these ports on servers that have protocols.

133
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:55,640
 And then we can build software on our clients

134
00:05:55,640 --> 00:05:58,680
 that talk these protocols.

135
00:05:58,680 --> 00:06:01,040
 The one we're going to be playing with the most

136
00:06:01,040 --> 00:06:02,680
 in development mode is port 80.

137
00:06:02,680 --> 00:06:08,000
 And in production mode, port 443 for the HTTP for web documents,

138
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,760
 basically in web application documents.

139
00:06:10,760 --> 00:06:13,520
 So up next, we're going to take a quick look at the hypertext

140
00:06:13,520 --> 00:06:15,080
 transfer protocol.

141
00:06:15,080 --> 00:06:17,840
 I always want to call it hypertext transport protocol,

142
00:06:17,840 --> 00:06:19,000
 HTTP.

143
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:24,520
 And that is the protocol that we talk to port 80 or port 443.

